First off, I need to understand what is meant by "mindset." From what I recall, mindset refers to the set of beliefs or attitudes that shape how we perceive and interact with the world. There are different types of mindsets, but I think the most relevant one here is the growth mindset versus the fixed mindset, a concept popularized by psychologist Carol Dweck.

In a fixed mindset, people believe that their qualities and abilities are static and unchangeable. They might fear change because it could expose their weaknesses or challenge their self-perception. On the other hand, a growth mindset suggests that abilities and intelligence can be developed through effort and learning. People with a growth mindset are more open to change because they see it as an opportunity to learn and grow.

